2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226010629/http://www.bpnews.net/34378|archivedate=25 December 2014|newspaper=Baptist Press|date=5 January 2011}}</ref>\n| residence      = [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], U.S.\n| website        = [http://www.meetrickcrawford.com/ Rick Crawford for Congress]\n}}\n\n'''Eric Alan \"Rick\" Crawford''' (born January 22, 1966)<ref>http://news.yahoo.com/s/cq/20101103/pl_cq_politics/politics000003758279</ref> is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|AR|1}} since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Before he was elected to Congress, Crawford was a radio announcer, businessman and a soldier in the [[U.S. Army]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nCrawford was born in the [[Homestead Air Force Base]] in [[Florida]], the son of Ruth Anne and Donny J. \"Don\" Crawford.<ref>http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/crawford.htm</ref> Crawford grew up in a military family. His father served in the [[United States Air Force]]. He graduated from [[Alvirne High School]] in [[Hudson, New Hampshire]]. He enlisted in the Army, where he served as an [[Explosive Ordnance Disposal|explosive ordnance disposal technician]] for four years,<ref>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Stiles | title = National Review: Turning Arkansas Red | date = 2010-10-27 | url = http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130855895 | work = [[National Public Radio]] | accessdate = 2010-10-31 }}</ref> while advancing to the rank of [[Sergeant]]. After his service, he attended [[Arkansas State University]] and graduated in 1996 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.S.]] in Agriculture Business and Economics.\n\n== Radio career ==\nHe has been a [[news anchor]] and agri-reporter on [[KAIT-TV]] in [[Jonesboro, Arkansas|Jonesboro]] and Farm Director on [[KFIN|KFIN-FM]]. He owned and operated the AgWatch Network, a farm news network heard on 39 radio stations in Arkansas, Missouri, Tennessee, Mississippi and Kentucky.\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Arkansas, 2010#District 1*}}\nCrawford decided to run for [[Arkansas' 1st congressional district]] after Democratic incumbent U.S. Congressman [[Robert Marion Berry|Marion Berry]] decided to retire. Crawford received the endorsements of Minnesota Governor [[Tim Pawlenty]], former Arkansas Governor [[Mike Huckabee]], former Congressman [[Asa Hutchinson]], and former Congressman [[Ed Bethune]].<ref>http://www.meetrickcrawford.com/endorsements/</ref> He won the Republican primary, defeating [[Princella Smith]] 72%-28%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=572929</ref> He won the general election, defeating Berry's chief of staff [[Chad Causey]] 52%-43%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=487762</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Arkansas, 2012#District 1*}}\nCrawford won re-election to a second term, defeating Democratic prosecutor, Scott Ellington, 56%-39%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=705041</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nCrawford was sworn into office on January 5, 2011 as a member of the 112th Congress.  He is the first Republican to represent his district in Washington since [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. Crawford is a member of the [[Republican Study Committee]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}\n\nCrawford voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and to return federal non-security spending to fiscal year 2008 levels.  He also voted to terminate taxpayer financing of presidential election campaigns and party conventions.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}\n\nIn 2010 Crawford signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2010/04/crawford-rick.pdf</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn January 18, 2013, Crawford introduced the [[Farmers Undertake Environmental Land Stewardship Act (H.R. 311; 113th Congress)]] into the House.<ref name=311sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 311 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/311|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> The bill would require the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) to modify the Spill Prevention, Control, and Countermeasure (SPCC) rule, which regulates oil discharges into navigable waters and adjoining shorelines.<ref name=cbo311>{{cite web|title=H.R. 311 - CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/44719|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> The rule requires certain farmers to develop an [[oil spill]] prevention plan that is certified by a professional [[engineer]] and may require them to make [[infrastructure]] changes.<ref name=\"cbo311\"/> According to supporters, this bill would \"ease the burden placed on farmers and ranchers\" by making it easier for smaller farms to self-certify and raising the level of storage capacity under which farms are exempted.<ref name=HighPlainsJ1>{{cite news|title=Committee passes legislation to ease burden of SPCC program|url=http://www.hpj.com/archives/2013/dec13/dec23/1104FUELSActsr.cfm|accessdate=11 March 2014|newspaper=High Plains Journal|date=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Department Operations, Oversight, and Credit|Subcommittee on Department Operations, Oversight, and Credit]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Nutrition and Horticulture|Subcommittee on Nutrition and Horticulture]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n*[[Republican Study Committee]]\n\n==Personal life==\nCrawford and his wife, Stacy, live in [[Jonesboro, Arkansas|Jonesboro]] with their children. He attends Nettleton Baptist Church, a [[Southern Baptist]] church in Jonesboro.<ref name=\"Baptist\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://crawford.house.gov/ Congressman Rick Crawford] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.meetrickcrawford.com/ Rick Crawford for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Arkansas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Rick_Crawford_%5BR-1%5D|Rick Crawford}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = C001087 | ballot = Rick_Crawford | nndb = 542/000257768 | votesmart = 119208 | govtrack = 412400 | opencong = 412400 | rollcall = 31216 | politifact = | fec = H0AR01083 | opensecrets = N00030770 | assets = rick-crawford | legistorm = 2729/Rep_Rick_Crawford_AR.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/Rick_Crawford.htm | congress = eric-crawford/1989 | worldcat = | c-span = rickcrawford03 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAlMfVKP }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n|state=Arkansas\n|district=1\n|before=[[Robert Marion Berry|Marion Berry]]\n|after=Incumbent|years=January 3, 2011 &ndash; present}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Cicilline]]<br><small>D-[[Rhode Island]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=280th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeff Denham]]<br><small>R-[[California]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{AR-FedRep}}\n{{U.S. Arkansas Representatives}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              =Crawford, Rick\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     = 1966-01-22\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = [[Homestead Air Force Base]], [[Florida]]\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawford, Rick}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:American radio reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Arkansas Republicans]]\n[[Category:Arkansas State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:People from Jonesboro, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Southern Baptists]]\n[[Category:United States Army personnel]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]"}]}}}}